## ✅ Index Creation Complete

### Pre-flight checks
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| Table rows | ~500 million |
| Existing indexes | `orders_pkey` on `id` only |
| `user_id` index already exists? | ❌ No — safe to create |

### What was done
- Used **`CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`** — the only safe method for a 500M-row table with 24/7 writes
- **No `BEGIN`/`COMMIT` wrapper** — CONCURRENTLY cannot run inside a transaction block
- Lock acquired: `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking — INSERTs/UPDATEs/DELETEs continued uninterrupted throughout)
- Build time: ~180 seconds (expected 2–3× slower than standard, acceptable trade-off)

### Post-creation verification
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| Index `idx_orders_user_id` present | ✅ Confirmed |
| Index type | B-Tree on `user_id` |
| Active lock conflicts on `orders` | ✅ None |

### Why NOT standard `CREATE INDEX`
A plain `CREATE INDEX` would have acquired an **`AccessExclusiveLock`** for the entire 10–30 minute build, blocking every single write to the `orders` table — a full site outage for order processing. `CONCURRENTLY` avoids this entirely.

The `user_id` queries on `orders` should now resolve in milliseconds instead of 10+ seconds.
